<br>
I'm curious as to what you think this mockery is.  The newness of anything will eventually fade.  There have been several improvements that were for the better.<br>
<br>
I remember complaints about soul binders.  Sure, maybe inanimant objects would have been better as oppose to a person who just stands around binding people, but the idea of easing the reliance on others for a bind is a good one.  Ever try to get a bind in Grobb or Cabilis at 2am in the old days?<br>
<br>
And yes, the PoK books make it so people can zip around the world faster than ever before without need of a druid or a wizard.  I was surprised when some from the port classes actually complained about this, as most of the time many of them complained about constantly getting tells for ports.  But this is a great feature for the casual player who gets to spend more time playing the game, instead of spending a good chunk of time just trying to get somewhere so that they can play the game.  That 15 minutes waiting for a boat and then the 7-10 minute ride itself, or the varying amount of time it took to get a port are huge timesinks when you only have one or two hours to play.<br>
<br>
EverQuest has evolved.  If it didn't, I doubt many of us would still be playing 4 and a half years later.  I have many fond memories of my beginnings all those years ago, as well; some of which I had forgotten until I read this thread.  But I don't believe the game we play today is a mockery of what it used to be.  It has simply evolved.  The best parts of the evolution are those that have reduced the frustration factors the game used to have.  There are still new adventures to be had, and places to explore, challenges to overcome, and quests to be solved.<br>
<br>
Just because there are spoiler sites, that doesn't mean you have to use them.  You want to maintain that sense of the unknown, that sense of wonder, that sense of danger?  Solve quests on your own, don't look them up.  Explore a new area without a printed out map on hand.  Go to an under-utilized zone or dungeon.  Don't always play it safe.  Don't always settle for your safe little group, in the same safe area you've &quot;exp grinded&quot; in a dozen times where you know exactly what to expect.    <br>
<br>
